@article{chenAIdrivenAnalysisPatient2026,
  title = {{{AI-driven}} Analysis of Patient Safety Reports Using Large Language Models: {{An}} Exploratory Multiple Methods Study},
  shorttitle = {{{AI-driven}} Analysis of Patient Safety Reports Using Large Language Models},
  author = {Chen, Kevin and Rogers, Kiley and Haberkorn, William and Lew, Matthew and Kanegan, Jeanmarie and Nam, Haemi and Chantra, Jean and Asch, Steven M and Lee, Grace M},
  year = 2026,
  month = jan,
  journal = {BMJ Quality \& Safety},
  pages = {bmjqs-2025-019495},
  issn = {2044-5415, 2044-5423},
  doi = {10.1136/bmjqs-2025-019495},
  urldate = {2026-02-05},
  abstract = {Introduction               Patient safety event reporting systems are widely used, yet organisations face challenges analysing the high volume of incident reports. While low-harm events represent the majority of submissions, they are rarely examined systematically due to the time and resources required to manually review the complex, lengthy, narrative data. Emerging technology like large language models (LLMs) offers new opportunities to address this gap. This study aimed to develop and evaluate an artificial intelligence-driven approach to identify patient safety issues, uncover system-level trends and assess readiness for implementation within a US healthcare system.                                         Methods               We quantitatively evaluated OpenAI's GPT-4o model accuracy in analysing patient safety event reports and qualitatively assessed pre-implementation outcomes. The LLM extracted safety problems from 9357 free-text narratives and then generated a taxonomy of `parent' and `child' subcategories. The model labelled every report's problem list using the taxonomy, and dashboards were developed to visualise trends. Patient safety experts reviewed two separate subsets of reports (n=100\,and n=219) to validate the LLM's accuracy. We conducted 10 stakeholder interviews to assess the dashboards' acceptability, appropriateness and adoption.                                         Results               The LLM had scores of 94\% mean agreement among reviewers in identifying problems, and 91.5\% and 83.3\%\,agreement in assigning `parent' and `child' category labels, respectively. The model identified previously hidden patterns of patient safety issues. Stakeholders described LLM-generated insights as clear, appropriate and valuable for their work. They perceived few barriers to adoption and believed the model could expedite manual report reviews and support system-level quality improvement.                                         Conclusion               LLMs offer an approach to capture and analyse multidimensional concepts in patient safety reports. By extracting problem summaries and categorising them into an accepted taxonomy, they can expose previously unidentified trends and provide visibility into system-level risks. LLMs could effectively augment and expedite manual reviews of safety events, while guiding prioritisation of quality and safety interventions.},
  langid = {english},
  keywords = {RQ1,Sec-LitReview,Sec-Methods,Status-NotesComplete},
  note = {\section{Chen et al. 2026}

\begin{quotation}

\par
\textbf{Cornerstone Article} --- One of three foundational papers for dissertation literature review and proposal. See also: [[Pitcher\_2022]], [[Das\_2021]]
\par
\end{quotation}

\subsection{Citation}

\par
Chen, K., Rogers, K., Haberkorn, W., Lew, M., Kanegan, J., Nam, H., Chantra, J., Asch, S. M., \& Lee, G. M. (2026). AI-driven analysis of patient safety reports using large language models: An exploratory multiple methods study. \emph{BMJ Quality \& Safety}. \href{https://doi.org/10.1136/bmjqs-2025019495}{https://doi.org/10.1136/bmjqs-2025019495}
\par
\subsection{My Notes \& Observations}

\subsubsection{Why This Paper Matters}

\par
This paper is \textbf{pure gold} for my dissertation. It's not just content validation---it's a template for how to structure an LLM-based safety report analysis study. The medical field faces the same research gap as aviation: traditional NLP/ML has limitations, and LLMs offer a path forward. The iron is hot.
\par
These researchers are using GPT-4o to extract safety issues from patient safety event reports---exactly what I'm doing with FAA UAS sighting reports. Different domain, same methodology. This gives me cross-domain evidence for my approach.
\par
\subsubsection{Key Findings (Consolidated)}

\begin{enumerate}

\item 
\par
\textbf{89\% human-LLM agreement} --- Most disagreements were alternative classifications, not hallucinations or gross misinterpretations
\par
\item 
\par
\textbf{Prompt engineering is essential} --- "Due to the high variability of text...significant prompt engineering was required to ensure accurate problem identification and avoid hallucinations"
\par
\item 
\par
\textbf{Volume justification} --- "Since the sheer volume of lower-harm events typically far exceeds the human resources required to conduct formal reviews...our findings demonstrate AI's potential to support proactive patient safety"
\par
\item 
\par
\textbf{Core outcome} --- "LLM-generated insights have the potential to augment patient safety workflows and reduce analytical burden"
\par
\item 
\par
\textbf{Hallucination definition} --- "LLM-generated outputs that appear plausible but are factually incorrect or fabricated, occurring when the model's predicted word sequences are not verified or grounded in evidence"
\par
\item 
\par
\textbf{Practical challenges} --- LLM interpreting suggestions/recommendations as facts, extracted issues too similar, assumptions within reports
\par
\end{enumerate}

\subsubsection{Key Structural Observations}

\par
\textbf{Abstract Layout:} Love this format---skips the lit review, goes straight to methods {$\rightarrow$} results {$\rightarrow$} conclusion. Perfect recipe. My published article followed this implicitly; now I can be explicit about it.
\par
\textbf{Methods Opener:} "Our study used multiple methods." Great topic sentence. My version: "This study involved eight phases" or similar. Compare this to my study design when building the final outline.
\par
\textbf{Genre Analysis Target:} Place this side-by-side with Pitcher and Das when building the dissertation outline. Use Chen's study design structure as a comparison point.
\par
\subsubsection{Methodological Insights}

\par
\textbf{Infrastructure:} They used Azure OpenAI via Python with Microsoft tenant. R might work with Azure, but adds complexity. For dissertation, stick with current infrastructure. For future NTSB/ASRS work or commercial consulting with sensitive data, this private cloud approach may be necessary.
\par
\textbf{Prompt Engineering:} "Due to the high variability of text...significant prompt engineering was required to ensure accurate problem identification and avoid hallucinations." \textbf{HIGHLY IMPORTANT.} This justifies my complex prompt methodology. They documented the issue well but don't share the specific prompts. I can do better in my dissertation.
\par
\textbf{Taxonomy Generation Concern:} They let the LLM drive taxonomy creation without predefined concepts. I'm skeptical---this doesn't help me build my codebook. My approach: pre-built codebook with LLM allowed to name columns using my coding principles. "We used LLM in the process but put harnesses on it."
\par
\textbf{The Explosion Problem:} 15,635 unique problems from 9,357 reports = \textasciitilde 2 problems per report. 8,652 from 2,065 reports = \textasciitilde 4 per report. This is exactly the Atlas.ai problem---you create MORE work than manual analysis. They don't mention the heavy lifting for category generation. This validates my decision to avoid pure qualitative analysis.
