  urldate = {2025-12-28},
  abstract = {Because of recent technological advancements, a growing number of unmanned aircraft systems (UASs) are anticipated to occupy the U.S. National Airspace System (NAS) and operate side-by-side with human pilot controlled civil aircraft. UAS technology has transitioned to broader applications, including commercial, scientific, and expanded military use. There have been significant challenges concerning the safe and suitable integration of UASs with existing systems. The interaction between humans and increasingly automated systems is of concern to researchers. Additionally, the number of UAS sightings has increased significantly during the last few years. In this study, the research team compiled 7,400 reports of UAS sightings (2015--2018). The Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA) method was then applied to develop topics relevant to UAS sighting incidents. This study also developed an online interactive tool to show keywords associated with different topics. These interactive topic models can help policymakers establish new policies and regulations to address specific safety concerns.},
  langid = {english},
  keywords = {machine learning,natural language processing,RQ1,RQ2-Narrative,Sec-LitReview,Status-NotesComplete,text mining,uas},
  note = {The author conducted a mixed methods approach to the UAS Sighting database for the years 2015-2018. ~Exploratory data analysis was conducted to characterize the overall data of the 7,400 reports finding that overall trend for those years as increasing and observed seasonal effects with the highest number of sightings in the summer. There a numerous figures and tables visualizing the data with varying levels or readability and usefulness.
\par
This article is valuable to my research because the author used several concepts I am attempting to employ.
\par
(1) Effective data visualization techniques - there a re several figures that are useful and several that could be iteratively improved
\par
(2) An LDA analysis dashboard was created and posted to GitHub. The LDA analysis tool is very simple and easy to understand, but the front-end design and UI could be greatly improved. ~I bookmarked the repo and tool. ~Tool is hosted on GitHub Pages.
\par
(3) The conclusion are pretty thin based on data. ~Reasoning from keyword analysis to overall conclusion could be developed more.
\par
This article will be an essential reference for my literature review. There are numerous lesson learned and ideas worth developing further in this research.
\par
``Other reports contradicted themselves, or included obvious mistakes. One incident near Green Airport in Rhode Island (PVD) was recorded as having occurred at Plovdiv Airport in Bulgaria (PDV).'' (Gettinger and Michel, 2015, pp. -) This specific record created issues in my data extraction pipeline -- the hybrid LLM-model eventually helped reconfigure the report correctly by identifying the transposition typo.

This particular quote provide context for the case to use AI/ML in the analysis of reports.
\par
``incident altitude, proximity to airports, drone-to-aircraft proximity, manned aircraft type, drone type, and incident time'' (Gettinger and Michel, 2015, pp. -) This the data extracted from the narrative studies
\par
``We considered each report on a case-by-case basis and, whenever possible, drew from other sources such as the NASA ASRS and SAFECOM databases, as well as media reports.'' (Gettinger and Michel, 2015, p. 10)
\par
Five solutions presented to reduce drone collision risks with manned aircraft:
\par
\begin{itemize}

\item Geo-fencing
\item Sense and avoid
