@inproceedings{howardFAAUnmannedAircraft2023,
  title = {{{FAA}} Unmanned Aircraft Systems ({{UAS}}) Sighting Reports: {{A}} Preliminary Survey},
  shorttitle = {{{FAA}} Unmanned Aircraft Systems ({{UAS}}) Sighting Reports},
  booktitle = {{{AIAA AVIATION}} 2023 {{Forum}}},
  author = {Howard, Ralph O.},
  year = 2023,
  month = jun,
  publisher = {{American Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics}},
  address = {San Diego, CA and Online},
  doi = {10.2514/6.2023-4099},
  urldate = {2025-12-28},
  abstract = {A preliminary analysis was conducted of 1,317 U.S. Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) Unmanned Aircraft Systems (UAS) sighting reports collected from the period July 1, 2020 to March 31, 2021. This set is the three most recent calendar quarters of reports recorded by FAA between November 2014 and March 2021, and represents 11\% of the total 11,694 reports available. The purpose of this study was to enhance basic knowledge concerning the nature and presence of drones in U.S. airspace; explore the possibility that UAP are recorded in the FAA data; and contribute towards enhanced aviation safety. The sighting reports, almost all originating from pilots, were screened for valid altitude information, confirmation that the recorded incident involved a UAS above ground level (AGL), and duplication. The 1,235 reports remaining were sorted and further reviewed for altitude ranges, instances of close approaches to aircraft, event time of day, UAS descriptions, and any noted characteristics. An unexpectedly large number of drones were found to be flying at surprisingly high altitudes across the U.S. In fact, 93\% (1,144 of the 1,235) were flying higher than the FAA legal limit of 400 feet (ft) above ground level; 72\% percent (889/1,235) were at or above 1,400 ft; 32\% (398/1,235) were at or above 4,100 ft; and 13\% (156/1,235) were at or above 8,200 ft. Most observations were made during the day, with 90\% (1,109/1,235) reporting daylight viewing. Descriptions of UAS vary widely in size, shape and appearance. Just over half of the report descriptions included color (645/1,235), with some recording multiple colors. In the 645 cases, there were 831 separate notations of color; the colors reported most often were black, white, red, silver, and gray, together comprising more than 80\% of the 831 notations. Relatively few reports 16\% (197/1,235) had a physical description of the UAP beyond its color. Among these 197 reports, most described were quadcopter drones (165); the others were balloon (17), fixed-wing drone (12), and ``object'' (3). Size descriptions were found in 8\% of the reports (96 of 1,235) and these ranged from ``small'' to ``large,'' although the terms are relative and not defined. Of the 60 ``small'' or ``medium'' UAS, 21 were observed at more than 4,000 feet AGL, where steady wind becomes a factor. Shapes were rarely reported (13 reports); round, spherical or oval shapes (7 reports) were the most common. These 13 reports of shape included such unusual descriptions as ``elliptical, silver-colored drone,'' ``shiny chrome, oval shaped, UAS with a red stripe,'' and ``medium-sized, bubble-shaped UAS.'' Other unusual descriptions included ``UAS with two engines'' and ``gray, 4 meters long UAS.'' Close approaches, one of the primary hazards of UAP, occurred in 20\% (241/1,235) of the reports, where UAS flew within an estimated 500 feet of an aircraft in flight. A majority of these close approaches (160) occurred within 300 feet or less. Nine incidents required the reporting aircraft to take evasive maneuvers, and in six, Near-Miss Air Collisions (NMACs) were reported. The FAA is expecting that the number of drones in operation will increase greatly, and possibly double, over the next 1-2 years. Adjusting this study's 9-month findings to one year and assuming a modest increase of 33\% in the total number of drones flying in 2023, the data suggest that 2023 FAA UAS reports could include more than 2,000 drones flying above 400 ft and 1,500 above 4,000 ft; and more than 400 UAS close approaches to aircraft. However, attributing all UAS sightings to drones is problematic in view of the legal and technical difficulties of effective drone performance at high altitudes, such as steady winds, decreasing temperatures below freezing, and the difficulty of control at great distances. Whatever the nature of the reported UAS, potential risks to civil aviation are apparent.},
  isbn = {978-1-62410-704-7},
  langid = {english},
  keywords = {RQ-General,Sec-LitReview,Status-NotesComplete},
  note = {\section{Annotations\\
(12/28/2025, 6:24:20 PM)}

\par
``However, careful review of the report entries from the standpoint of identifying what was observed, indicates that in the great majority of reports, there is very limited information that is useful'' (Howard, 2023, p. 3)
\par
``Due to the quantity of numbers in the ``Summary'' column, abundant abbreviations, and variation in the wording that appears, extracting the altitudes of both UAS and aircraft altitudes required the careful reading of each entry'' (Howard, 2023, p. 4)
\par
``Standard Excel commands were used to sort and classify the initial set of 1,317 repor'' (Howard, 2023, p. 4)
\par
``but no comprehensive investigations of the UAS reports, evaluating all of the issued spreadsheets or a subset of them, could be found'' (Howard, 2023, p. 4) This is factually incorrect---several studies had been conducted at this point.
\par
``72\% (889) were at or above 1,400 ft, more than 1,000 ft above the FAA limit'' (Howard, 2023, p. 4)
\par
``32\% (398) were at/above 4,100 ft, and 13\% (156) were at/above 8,200 ft. The possible significance of these latter two benchmarks will be discussed further below. As shown in the figure, almost half (48\%) of the reports place the UAS at between 2,401 and 13,400 ft AGL.'' (Howard, 2023, p. 4) I want to plot this\dots{} let's look deeper.
\par
``Problems Affecting Drone/UAS Operations at High Altitudes'' (Howard, 2023, p. 8)
\par
``Remote ID'' (Howard, 2023, p. 10)
\par
``identity, location, and altitude of the drone and its control station or take-off locatio'' (Howard, 2023, p. 10)
\par
``weighing more than 0.55 pounds'' (Howard, 2023, p. 10)
\par
``The Final Rule for Remote ID became effective with the Rule issuance in April 2021, and set out a 29-month transition period for drone operators'' (Howard, 2023, p. 10)
\par
The author of this article conducts quantitative research on the FAA Drone Sighting Database. ~Only 11\% of the reports were analyzed and the author acknowledges that he conducted a manual review of the information. ~He utilized the ``search and Find'' functions of Microsoft excel and did not use more advanced methods. The author also seems to have missed the 6-8 other articles that conducted similar research on the database as he claims, ``but no comprehensive investigations of the UAS reports, evaluating all of the issued spreadsheets or a subset of them, could be found.''
\par
The author provides some critical analysis of the reports, primarily in their value to identifying UAP. ~Several of the items he critiqued:duration of the
\par
\begin{itemize}

\item duration of the sighting
\item missing shapes
\item movement of the of the UAS
\item how many crewmembers saw the UAS
\item if ATC or RADAR return could confirm the UAS
\item and size was rarely noted

\end{itemize}

\par
Howard seems interested in the value of the database to identify UAP phenomena and any useful data to help identify UAP. ~Based on the interest of UAP, he scrutinizes the pilot reports especially at higher altitudes and is critical of reported drone shapes. My perspective is that throughout the discussion he seems to assert that many of the high altitude encounters were unlikely and due to illegality and may be indicative of UAP, not UAS.

Of the 36 references only (1) one source was a peer-reviewed article in an academic article. 14 articles were from government sources, 12 from the FAA, 2 from ODNI. There were articals from NARCAP, National Aviation Reporting Center on Anomalous Phenomena which is non-profit organization run by volunteers and does not peer-review thier published articles.
\par
Lastly the value of this article should be questioned despite being presented at AIAA Aviation Forum and found in an academic journal. Howard's analysis of FAA UAS sighting reports was not peer-reviewed and presented under the auspices of the Scientific Coalition for UAP Studies (SCU), an organization with an explicit interest in identifying UAP in aviation data. The author's background as a former MUFON Georgia State Director and the paper's stated purpose of exploring "the possibility that UAP are recorded in the FAA data" suggest potential confirmation bias in case selection and interpretation. These factors warrant caution when considering the paper's conclusions regarding high-altitude UAS sightings that the author suggests may not be attributable to conventional drones.
\par
\section{Annotations\\
(12/28/2025, 6:24:20 PM)}

\par
``However, careful review of the report entries from the standpoint of identifying what was observed, indicates that in the great majority of reports, there is very limited information that is useful'' (Howard, 2023, p. 3) {$<$}- \textbf{Many would disagree with the characteriztion of this standpoint, DaS (2021) \& Gettinger \& Michel (2015)}
\par
``Due to the quantity of numbers in the ``Summary'' column, abundant abbreviations, and variation in the wording that appears, extracting the altitudes of both UAS and aircraft altitudes required the careful reading of each entry'' (Howard, 2023, p. 4)
\par
``Standard Excel commands were used to sort and classify the initial set of 1,317 reports'' (Howard, 2023, p. 4)
\par
``but no comprehensive investigations of the UAS reports, evaluating all of the issued spreadsheets or a subset of them, could be found'' (Howard, 2023, p. 4) {$<$}- \textbf{This is factually incorrect---several studies had been conducted at this point.}
\par
``72\% (889) were at or above 1,400 ft, more than 1,000 ft above the FAA limit'' (Howard, 2023, p. 4)
\par
``Overall, the entries present a disparate and confusing range of UAS appearances, altitudes, and distances from the reporting aircraft.'' (Howard, 2023, p. 3)
\par
``32\% (398) were at/above 4,100 ft, and 13\% (156) were at/above 8,200 ft. The possible significance of these latter two benchmarks will be discussed further below. As shown in the figure, almost half (48\%) of the reports place the UAS at between 2,401 and 13,400 ft AGL.'' (Howard, 2023, p. 4) I want to plot this\dots{} let's look deeper.
\par
``Problems Affecting Drone/UAS Operations at High Altitudes'' (Howard, 2023, p. 8)
\par
``Remote ID'' (Howard, 2023, p. 10)
\par
``identity, location, and altitude of the drone and its control station or take-off locatio'' (Howard, 2023, p. 10)
\par
``weighing more than 0.55 pounds'' (Howard, 2023, p. 10)
\par
``The Final Rule for Remote ID became effective with the Rule issuance in April 2021, and set out a 29-month transition period for drone operators'' (Howard, 2023, p. 10)
\par
\subsection{List of extracted data:}

\begin{quotation}

\par
``Each Excel file is a formatted, 4-column table, and each line-item entry (i.e., report) provides four items in four columns: 

1) the incident date; 

2) the state; 

3) the city of the reporting airport; and in the fourth column, 

4) ``Summary,'' a description of the incident.'' (Howard, 2023, p. 3)

``The summary provides an additional ten specific items:

5) a notation of to whom the report was made, which could be a large metropolitan airport, military air base, county airport, or other facility; 

6) the type of aircraft reporting (e.g. Cessna 172, B767, etc.) and the origin-destination airport codes for its flight route; 

7) the 4-character (24-hour) time of the incident, including the time zone abbreviation; 

8) a description, if recorded, of characteristics (color, size, shape) of the UAS, although most reports lack this; 

9) the altitude of the UAS (altitude AGL in feet (ft)); 

10) the position of the UAS with respect to the aircraft (e.g. ``at the 2 o'clock position, 500 feet off the right wing''); 

11) direction of flight, and the altitude of the reporting aircraft (ft AGL); 

12) the general location, in miles, of the incident in relation to the reporting airport or another airport, city, or landmark and using abbreviations such as NE or SW; 

13) whether evasive action was taken by the aircraft; and 

14) whether law enforcement was notified and if so, whom. 

Thus, the data provided on each incident comprise fourteen (14) specific items.'' (Howard, 2023, p. 3)
\par
\end{quotation}

\par
Howard's paper is actually a useful inclusion in the literature review to help with
\par
\begin{enumerate}

\item \textbf{Establish the landscape} --- Others have looked at this database, including from a UAP angle

\item \textbf{Differentiate methodology} --- LLM-assisted extraction and comprehensive analysis versus his 11\% manual Excel review

\item \textbf{Demonstrate source evaluation skills} --- Recognizing that "indexed in a database" {$\neq$} "peer-reviewed" and that author affiliations matter

\item \textbf{Set up my contribution} --- If prior work has gaps (missed literature, limited methods, potential bias), my analysis is more complete an fill the gap.

\end{enumerate}},
  file = {/Users/mikehickey2/Zotero/storage/4T3UD5MR/Howard - 2023 - FAA Unmanned Aircraft Systems (UAS) Sighting Reports A Preliminary Survey.pdf;/Users/mikehickey2/Zotero/storage/4YJQJ9ML/Howard - 2023 - FAA Unmanned Aircraft Systems (UAS) Sighting Reports A preliminary survey.pdf;/Users/mikehickey2/Zotero/storage/UCF3W9TE/Howard - 2023 - FAA Unmanned Aircraft Systems (UAS) Sighting Reports A Preliminary Survey.pdf}
}

