  urldate = {2025-12-28},
  abstract = {Unmanned Aircraft System (UAS) growth in the past several years has been rising at a steady pace which has complicated the attempts to safely integrate them into the National Airspace System, as evidenced by an increasing number of UAS sighting reports being submitted to the Federal Aviation Administration. The analysis consisted of a mixed method approach using quantitative analysis of more than 9000 Federal Aviation Administration Unmanned Aircraft System Sighting reports from 2015 through 2019, as well as U.S. Census data, and weather data. The qualitative analysis focused on UAS regulation, and heatmap data of both population density and UAS sighting location density. The findings for the five states with the most and the least sighting reports show that major metropolitan areas, which have high population and population density, higher median household incomes, high percentage of college graduates, and are located in areas that have stable weather and negligible weather effects such as rain and high winds during the summer months, have both high and concentrated levels of UAS sightings.},
  langid = {english},
  keywords = {RQ-General,Sec-LitReview,Status-NotesComplete},
  note = {\section{Pitcher, 2022}

\subsection{Pitcher (2022) - Analysis of UAS Sightings Reports: Factors Leading to High Sighting Reports}

\subsection{Citation}

\par
Pitcher, S. E. (2022). Analysis of Unmanned Aircraft Systems Sightings Reports: Determination of Factors Leading to High Sighting Reports. \emph{Unmanned Systems}, 10(3), 205--239. https://doi.org/10.1142/S2301385022500121
\par
\subsection{Personal Observations}

\par
This article is an extension of Pitcher's earlier work with the Drone Sightings Near Airports data set. He included the entire data set that was available at the time of the report and encompassed 9,000 reports over approximately five years. His conclusions here are a lot more logical and seem more vetted than in his earlier work. He attempted to find a relationship to weather which would justify his earlier assertion that people fly in better weather (Pitcher \& Whealan-George, 2020).
\par
Additionally Pitcher looks at the relationship of UAS sightings and regulatory data. Specifically he attempts to use qualitative methods to draw out any potential correlations between UAS sightings trends that may align with regulatory measures that were enacted.
\par
Pitcher also used a third-party freelancer to develop his graphics using the QGIS data population overlaid with UAS Sightings Heatmap. This worked well for this particular study because it adds a lot of rich graphical visualizations to the paper. I would like to emulate similar graphics in my paper to provide visualizations of the extracted data fields.
\par
\subsubsection{Key Takeaways for My Research}

\begin{itemize}

\item The QGIS/Fiverr approach for heatmap development is replicable and cost-effective (\textasciitilde\$42)
\item Population density as confounding variable is critical consideration for my analysis
\item Weather correlation supports seasonal patterns in recreational UAS activity
\item Regulatory analysis found minimal impact -- interesting null finding
\item The freelancer workflow (geolocate {$\rightarrow$} QGIS {$\rightarrow$} Leaflet {$\rightarrow$} webmap) could inform my visualization pipeline

\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Directly Quotable for My Work}

\begin{quotation}

\par
"This heatmap results can mean one of two things, there are either more instances of unauthorized UAS flights in those high population areas, or there are more people around to witness and report such sightings and it does not signify why the selected states have higher occurrences of UAS sightings, just that there are clusters of more UAS sightings around major metropolitan areas" (p. 220)
\par
\end{quotation}

\par
This observation parallels the George Berkeley philosophical question ("If a tree falls in a forest and no one is around to hear it, does it make a sound?") and directly informs interpretation of sighting density data. Population density affects sighting through two modes: more people are there to fly AND more people are there to report.
\par
\subsubsection{Data Limitations Worth Noting}

\begin{quotation}

\par
"Sighting data can also be limited as only individuals familiar with UAS who know how to file a report, or those who care to file a sighting report on unauthorized UAS usage will make it into the reported data." (p. 206)
\par
\end{quotation}

\par
This is a critical limitation of the Drone Sightings Near Airports dataset: Reporters may not know how to file reports so the report never makes it to the database. Someone may see a drone and not care to report it, leading to underreporting.
\par
\subsection{Overview}

\par
This mixed-methods study analyzes 9,467 FAA UAS sighting reports from 2015--2019 to identify factors contributing to higher sighting incidence across U.S. states. The research combines quantitative analysis (Chi-Square Goodness-of-Fit tests) with qualitative examination of regulations, census demographics, weather patterns, and GIS heatmap comparisons. Key finding: major metropolitan areas with high population density, higher median household incomes, college-educated populations, and favorable summer weather have both high and concentrated levels of UAS sightings.
\par
\subsection{Research Questions \& Methods}

\subsubsection{RQ1: Geographic and Demographic Factors}

