\subsection{Citation}

\par
Pitcher, S. E., \& Whealan-George, K. A. (2020). Can the timeframe of reported UAS sightings help regulators? \emph{Beyond: Undergraduate Research Journal}, 4, Article 3. https://commons.erau.edu/beyond/vol4/iss1/3
\par
\subsection{Personal Observations}

\par
This study was conducted on the "Drone Sightings Near Airports" dataset. It included all available data at the time which included three full years of sightings. The authors established that there is a significant seasonal trend in the data with May, June and then December, January being the highest months. They offer some ideas on how these trends are caused and advice to policymakers and aviators on how to address the trends.
\par
This is the foundational paper that Pitcher later expanded into his 2022 \emph{Unmanned Systems} publication. The methodology is straightforward---Chi-Square Goodness of Fit---and the findings are clear. However, the causal explanations offered are speculative rather than empirically established.
\par
\subsubsection{Key Lessons for My Research}

\par
\textbf{On Speculation vs. Causation:}
\par
\begin{quotation}

\par
"UAS flights spike as favorable weather draws out hobbyists, so June should have the most resources allocated to counter UAS threats. Also, December and January show increased sightings indicating that as holiday promotions spike, hobbyists and gift recipients begin their UAS careers." (p. 5)
\par
\end{quotation}

\par
There is speculation here---likely valid speculation---but no causal relationship is determined in this study other than proving there is statistically significant seasonality in the data. There are likely regional differences in this data too. Someone might fly their drone in early spring or late fall if they live in the western desert like Phoenix or Vegas. \textbf{In my work I will need to heed this lesson learned when making assumptions or speculation about the causes of the data I find significant.}
\par
\textbf{On Dataset Growth and Longitudinal Claims:}
\par
\begin{quotation}

\par
"Data collected represented the entire reported time series of UAS sightings by the FAA beginning in June, 2015 and ending in June, 2018." (p. 3)
\par
\end{quotation}

\par
At the time of this study the authors used the entire dataset available. However, at that time it was only about three years worth of data. Now it is more than 4x as large and includes twelve years. Either way, it may not be fair to say that my work is the "only longitudinal study of the entire dataset" when next quarter it won't be anymore. \textbf{Need to review the language around this assertion to make sure we are getting it right.}
\par
\subsubsection{Publication Context}

\par
\emph{Beyond: Undergraduate Research Journal} is a peer-reviewed academic publication of Embry-Riddle Aeronautical University (ERAU), specifically managed by its Office of Undergraduate Research. This positions the work as student research with faculty mentorship (Whealan-George as co-author/advisor).
\par
\subsection{Overview}

\par
This study examines seasonal variation in FAA UAS sighting reports to help regulators and aviation safety managers allocate resources more effectively. Using Chi-Square Goodness of Fit analysis on 36 months of FAA data (June 2015--June 2018), the authors found statistically significant monthly variation, with June showing the highest sightings (favorable weather) and December/January showing secondary peaks (holiday gift season). The practical implication: counter-UAS resources should be concentrated during predictable high-activity periods.
\par
\subsection{Research Questions \& Methods}

\subsubsection{Explicit Research Questions}

\begin{enumerate}

\item \textbf{RQ1:} Does the month of the year have an impact on UAS sightings in the United States?
\item \textbf{RQ2:} Is there a difference between months of the year for sightings of UAS?

\end{enumerate}

