\subsection{Critical Analysis}

\subsubsection{Strengths}

\begin{itemize}

\item \textbf{Complete dataset:} Used entire available FAA archive at time of study
\item \textbf{Clear methodology:} Chi-Square Goodness of Fit is appropriate for categorical frequency data
\item \textbf{High statistical power:} Power = 1.0 indicates reliable results
\item \textbf{Practical application:} Directly actionable recommendations for resource allocation
\item \textbf{Transparent analysis:} Percent from expected clearly shows which months deviate

\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Limitations}

\begin{enumerate}

\item \textbf{Temporal scope:} Only 3 years of data; patterns may not hold over longer periods
\item \textbf{No regional analysis:} National aggregation may mask regional/climate variations
\item \textbf{Correlation {$\neq$} Causation:} Weather and holiday explanations are plausible but not tested
\item \textbf{No covariates:} Did not control for UAS market growth, regulatory changes, or reporting behavior
\item \textbf{Underreporting assumed:} Authors acknowledge sightings represent only reported incidents

\end{enumerate}

\subsubsection{Speculative Conclusions}

\par
The authors' causal explanations warrant scrutiny:
\par
\begin{quotation}

\par
"UAS flights spike as favorable weather draws out hobbyists"
\par
\end{quotation}

\par
This is reasonable but untested. Regional differences likely exist---desert climates may show different seasonal patterns than northern states.
\par
\begin{quotation}

\par
"December and January show increased sightings indicating that as holiday promotions spike, hobbyists and gift recipients begin their UAS careers"
\par
\end{quotation}

\par
Note that December has the \emph{lowest} raw count (92) but January (103) is also below average. The "holiday spike" interpretation applies to January more than December, and the deviation percentages (18\% and 13\%) indicate these months are significantly \emph{below} expected, not above. This appears to be a misinterpretation---the statistical significance indicates these months differ from expected, but the direction is \emph{lower} sightings, not higher.
\par
\textbf{Correction:} Upon re-reading, the authors seem to conflate "statistically different from expected" with "high sightings." December/January are significantly \emph{below} the expected average, likely due to weather, not showing a holiday "spike."
\par
