  abstract = {This paper examines the characteristics and implications of reported Unmanned Aircraft Systems (UAS) incidents in the National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) Aviation Safety Reporting System (ASRS) database for UAS incidents operated by remote pilots licensed under Part 107. Characteristics examined include seasonal patterns of incidents, operational mission, and number of contributing factors, as well as crew configuration, timing of incident detection, and airspace class. Results are compared with previous research and with incident data for recreational users. The narratives for each incident are assessed to provide a greater context for the incidents and to determine how the incidents vary in different classes of airspace. Findings reveal that UAS incidents often involve multiple contributing factors, including environmental, human, equipment, and policy issues; there is an increasing prevalence of human-related issues over equipment problems compared to previous research; this reflects historic safety trends in crewed aviation. Near-miss incidents with crewed aircraft are a very real concern, particularly in Class D airspace, which often includes general aviation (GA) and helicopter operations. This research underscores the need for timely communication during urgent nighttime UAS operations as well as enhanced safety culture at both operator and organizational levels.},
  langid = {english},
  keywords = {RQ2-Trends,Sec-LitReview,Status-NotesComplete},
  note = {\section{⁨Sun⁩ and ⁨Hubbard⁩ (2025)}

\par
\textbf{Purpose:\\
}1. To provide insights into the safety characteristics of reported incidents for Part 107 UAS operations; ~
\par
2. To compare the characteristics of current Part 107 operations with those of recreational UAS operations; ~
\par
3. To identify trends in UAS operations by comparing characteristics of current Part 107 operations with previous studies; ~
\par
4. To investigate incident characteristics in different classes of airspace. (Sun and Hubbard, 2025, p. 2)
\par
\textbf{Theoretical Frameworks:} 
\par
\begin{itemize}

\item \textbf{Heinrich's Iceberg Theory} is used as the motivating safety logic for studying incidents/precursors: catastrophic outcomes can arise from accumulated minor errors, violations, and hazards, so proactive incident analysis helps surface latent deficiencies
\item 
\par
\textbf{Human factors and systems safety frameworks} are used to interpret multi-causal incidents:
\par
\begin{itemize}

\item \textbf{SHELL model} (software, hardware, environment, liveware) as a human factors lens

\end{itemize}

\item \textbf{Swiss Cheese model} (multiple layers of defense; latent conditions + human performance variability)

\end{itemize}

\par
\textbf{Method: }
\par
\textbf{Design / data source:} Retrospective analysis of UAS incident reports from the \textbf{NASA ASRS} UAS reporting system (voluntary, confidential, non-punitive; introduced for UAS in 2019). 
\par
\textbf{Sample and timeframe:}
\par
\textbf{187} reports: Part 107 (commercial)
\par
\textbf{70} reports: recreational
\par
Time window: \textbf{2019 through June 2024} Sun and Hubbard - 2025 - An Exa\dots{}
\par
\textbf{Variables analyzed (examples):} time of occurrence (month/time of day), mission type, crew configuration, airspace class, time of detection (pre-flight/in-flight/post-flight), and contributing factors; categories were designed to be non-overlapping and aligned with standards/regulatory practice. 
\par
\begin{enumerate}

\item \textbf{Contributing factor coding:} Used \textbf{keywords} in the ASRS ``Assessment'' field, with \textbf{narrative review} to interpret meaning and assign each keyword to one contributing-factor category (environmental, equipment, human factors, policy).
\item \textbf{Analysis approach:} Descriptive statistics plus \textbf{chi-square goodness-of-fit tests} (5\% significance) to compare distributions across variables and between Part 107 vs recreational operations (and also comparisons to prior studies).

\end{enumerate}

\par
This article provides significant finding on the types of missions, conditions of flight, and excellent summaries of specific incident reports that were of interest. ~One of the major ideas I thought of while reading this paper is if we could prompt, train, and tune an LLM to provide summaries of narrative reports and provide statistical data regarding. ~Model selection would be pivotal for these tasks.
\par
\subsection{Annotations}

\par
``it is useful to examine UAS incidents to better understand the risks and safety context for UAS operations. This philosophy is supported by Heinrich's Iceberg Theory, which suggests that catastrophic accidents often stem from seemingly minor errors and safety hazards that may go unnoticed or unaddressed'' (Sun and Hubbard, 2025, p. 2)
\par
``UAS sighting reports prioritize documentation of public safety concerns and regulatory violations through a public reporting system. FAA sightings reports may be made by remote pilots, pilots of manned aircraft, air traffic controllers, airport operations workers, and even members of the general public.'' (Sun and Hubbard, 2025, p. 6)
\par
``The FAA will investigate the reports, and there may be penalties against a pilot if the FAA documents a violation. Since ASRS is non-punitive, a remote pilot may file a report in ASRS to protect themselves from a penalty if they believe there was a violation.'' (Sun and Hubbard, 2025, p. 6)
\par
``Building on Heinrich's (1972) Iceberg Theory [7], which suggests that catastrophic accidents often result from the accumulation of minor errors, violations, and hazards, it is imperative to proactively examine incident reports to identify and address latent safety deficiencies.'' (Sun and Hubbard, 2025, p. 22)},
  file = {/Users/mikehickey2/Zotero/storage/C5QA5AWL/Sun and Hubbard - 2025 - An Examination of UAS Incidents Characteristics and Safety Considerations.pdf}
}

