\subsection{My Notes \& Observations}

\subsubsection{Why This Paper Matters}

\par
This article is an 8/10 for relevance, not the 6/10 the initial AI assessment gave it. After reading it cover to cover with annotations, this is a cornerstone piece. It did a massive amount of synthesis work that directly feeds my literature review and discussion. The authors surveyed 175 studies on AI in aviation safety and came to many of the same conclusions I was already forming independently. Both validating and useful.
\par
The reference list alone is a goldmine. There are 10-12 highly relevant papers in their Tier 1 references that directly address LLM-based extraction from aviation safety narratives. Several are already in my Zotero, but the ones I'm missing need immediate acquisition. The article is so dense with citable material that every paragraph in the relevant sections has something I can use.
\par
What makes this a cornerstone and not just background: the authors think along the same lines as my literature. They continue to examine human-AI teaming, comparing methods like RAG and fine-tuning and prompt engineering and CoT prompting to maximize results. They arrive at similar conclusions about building trustworthiness between operator and model. Their work establishes the state of the art in aviation safety AI broadly, even though they have zero UAS/drone coverage, which actually reinforces my niche.
\par
\subsubsection{Initial Reading Impressions (Voice Notes)}

\par
Hey, this article is extremely relevant to my study. There's so much work that was done in here that I can just transfer into my literature review or my discussion areas. It does analysis and synthesis of these multiple different sources. It provides the current state of AI in the aviation safety analysis world. The AI model did a synthesis and analysis of this, recommends some different sources but only grades it as 6 out of 10 for relevance. I think it's gotta be more like an 8 out of 10 after actually going through it. And it triggered so many really great dots in the annotation section that I need to take a look at. I need to mark this as a cornerstone article to be pointed at during my literature review and during my discussion. There's just like I said so much work that was already synthesized and reasoned through and it sounds like these authors are thinking right along the same lines as the literature that I was. In the sense of continuing to look at human-AI teaming to look at different methods like RAG and fine-tuning and prompt engineering and chain of thought prompting to maximize results. The authors come up with similar conclusions about future advancements in AI specifically to build trustworthiness between the operator and the model. They talk very deeply about augmenting the human versus an AI-led or an AI-driven analysis. There are several really good diagrams in here, although simplistic in the presentation, they can really help a reader build their knowledge of what is being said on some of these complex topics. There's some really good descriptions in plain language of some of the concepts being used in the current state of AI in aviation safety analysis. There are so many citable items throughout this and my annotations and my synthesis is included in a lot of those annotation notes as well.
\par
Overall there's tons of value in this article that can be taken and I just need to synthesize all of this stuff again. It needs probably a good second, third, or maybe in a fourth read to digest it all. It's pretty detailed; every sentence has a ton of value. Every sentence is pretty well written in the sense of explaining things. Every paragraph has a really good flow in some places, other places are kind of dabbles in some irrelevance. So there are significant portions of the article that I can just pretty much disregard. But when it comes to narrative data extraction and data analysis, this thing is chock-full of really great information.
\par
\subsubsection{Key Insights for My Dissertation}

\subsubsubsection{Methodological Validation}

\par
Multiple studies in this review use the exact same techniques I'm employing: chain of thought prompting, prompt engineering, fine-tuning. This "100\% justifies the use of my method" (my words from annotation, p. 6). The authors note that researchers are "tackling deficiency with model fine-tuning with prompt engineering and other methods to gain domain-specific knowledge" (p. 6). That is my study in a sentence.
\par
The critical gap I noticed: a lot of people are using LLMs for accident analysis, hazard identification, and classification tasks, but I'm not sure anybody was putting extracted information into structured data fields and then analyzing the variables afterward. That's my contribution. The extraction-to-analysis pipeline, not just classification.
\par
The growing trend from ML/DL to LLM-based reasoning in accident analysis (p. 6) validates the timing of my research. The field is moving in this direction, and the authors confirm it with quantitative evidence from their 175-study survey.
\par
\subsubsubsection{Chain of Thought (CoT) Prompting}

\par
Liu et al. (2025) [110] combined HFACS and CoT prompt design to analyze accidents and concluded that LLM outperformed human experts in inferring certain types of human errors (p. 6). This is directly relevant to my prompt engineering approach.
\par
The authors provide excellent plain-language descriptions of how CoT works:
\par
\begin{itemize}

\item "A step-by-step CoT can guide LLM to think according to the specified approach. Hence, it enhances the traceability of errors and provides a suitable explanation to each LLM action" (p. 11)
\item "This approach mitigates hallucinations and randomness in LLM so that human investigators can understand the logic behind LLM's response" (p. 11)
\item CoT breaks the main task into multiple subtasks (p. 11)

\end{itemize}

\par
These explanations are digestible for non-technical readers. I should emulate this style in my own methods section when explaining my prompting approach. The whole paragraph on p. 11 about CoT should be studied and referenced.
\par
\subsubsubsection{Trustworthiness \& Non-Determinism}

\par
Section 5.1 on trustworthiness is directly applicable to my discussion. The core tension: aviation demands deterministic, transparent, reproducible results. AI is non-deterministic. You can give it the same input several times and get different outcomes, especially without proper tuning. "A trustworthy AI should be transparent, reliable, and ethically designed for applications in safety-critical domains" (p. 10). I need to trace this reference.
\par
My take on this: AI is a good manipulator. If you're not critically evaluating every output, the polished grammar and confident tone can fool you into thinking the output is authoritative when it could be completely wrong. For practitioners who aren't questioning with high scrutiny, it would be easy to accept AI outputs at face value. This connects to my validation methodology (RQ1). The human annotation with inter-rater reliability is specifically designed to catch these issues.
\par
CoT and validation techniques are the trust-building mechanisms. The authors advocate for designing "inherently interpretable models, ensuring traceability, and embedding causal reasoning" (p. 11). This is what my 2\texttimes 2 factorial design tests. Does structured prompting (CoT) actually improve extraction quality?
\par
\subsubsubsection{Human-AI Teaming}

\par
The authors make a crucial point: "AI is not designed to replace humans but to augment human expertise" (p. 12). Both humans and AI have different strengths and limitations. The combined use should be symbiotic, producing better results from the team than from either working independently.
\par
They discuss bidirectional communication, shared mental models, and iterative refinement loops. However, their treatment is basic. They miss the practical techniques currently used in software engineering: hooks, customizable model configurations (like Claude Code or Codex), and multi-model checking where one AI reviews another's output. The iterative brainstorming, planning, and reviewing workflow that I use daily isn't reflected in the aviation literature yet.
\par
"While novel AI 'products' are essential, researchers often overlook an equally important aspect: how human operators adapt to these systems and how effective interaction between humans and AI agents can be achieved" (p. 12). This observation surfaces something important: sub-optimal AI output is almost always an operator skill issue, or a technological gap in the interface. Most output from any computer system comes down to operator input quality.
\par
\subsubsubsection{Models Used Across Studies}

\par
Fig. 4 shows model distribution across studies:
\par
\begin{itemize}

\item BERT: n=10 (most adopted, accessible, inexpensive)
\item GPT family: n=7 (OpenAI, strong reasoning, accident analysis)
\item Llama: n=5 (locally hosted, confidentiality, but requires technical setup)
\item Claude: 1 study
\item Google: 1 study

\end{itemize}

\par
The dominance of BERT and ChatGPT is likely accessibility-driven. Locally hosted models (Llama, Mistral) offer confidentiality and security advantages but take significant technical expertise to deploy. Not many studies discuss how they actually access or fine-tune these models. That practical gap is worth noting. The underrepresentation of Claude and Google means there is room for comparative model studies going forward. This supports my contribution.
\par
\subsubsubsection{RAG as Future Research}

\par
The authors discuss RAG-aided causal identification from NTSB reports (p. 6). Reading this, I realized my approach to providing the NASR airport database alongside UAS sighting reports (so the LLM could identify airports using city/state and derive lat/long locations) is essentially a RAG-like pattern. I hadn't framed it that way.
\par
I'm not changing my current methods over this, but RAG is absolutely worth suggesting as a future research direction. The combination of CoT + prompt engineering + fine-tuning + RAG could be explored systematically. How these three (or four) techniques work together in a symbiotic fashion is still an open question.
\par
\subsubsubsection{Gaps I Noticed}

\begin{enumerate}

\item \textbf{No UAS/drone coverage.} Zero mentions of UAS, sUAS, drones, or unmanned systems. Confirms my research niche.
\item \textbf{Basic iterative process discussion.} The authors eventually get to iterative human-AI refinement (p. 13) but miss the depth of techniques available from software engineering and other fields.
\item \textbf{Missing practical details.} How do researchers actually access and configure these models? The engineering side is largely absent.
\item \textbf{LLM-vs-human lit review comparison.} Novel attempt (Section 5 comparison of human vs. Llama literature review), but underdone. No quantitative comparison. Interesting concept that could benefit from IRR techniques, but the immense volume makes it impractical. The finding: LLMs need fine-tuning and prompting to match human-level inference. Elementary for anyone working with LLMs, but novel for aviation.
\item \textbf{Justification for deferred RQ3.} Their discussion of predictive analysis using LLM (p. 6) validates the eventual NMAC pattern analysis I've deferred to future research.

\end{enumerate}

